Figure 5. Image analysis with ImageJ
(A) Obtaining region-of-interest (ROI) using macro based on a fluorescent image of Hoechst.
(B) Using the obtained ROIs to quantify signal intensities of CD34 and CD38 and their corresponding background signal intensity.
(C) Calculate the normalized intensity of each ROI and obtain counts of target cells (CD34+/CD38-/Hoechst cells).
Select “Measure” in the “ROI Manager” to obtain the raw signal intensity of CD34.
Use the rectangular selection tool of ImageJ to measure the background intensity at positions without cells (step 4a in Figure 5[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig5]B) and calculate the mean area of the background intensity.
Copy the background intensity and raw CD34 intensity into an Excel table.
Repeat steps 39–42 on the CD38 fluorescent image of the same cells (Figure 5[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig5]B).
In the Excel table containing the raw intensity and background intensity of CD34 and CD38, align the data based on ROI identities, and calculate the normalized intensity of each ROI according to the formulation shown in Figure 5[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig5]C.
Identify ROIs with CD34 Normalized Intensity > 0 and CD38 Normalized Intensity < 0 as target cells (Figure 5[href=https://www.wicell.org#fig5]C).
